org.jmisb.api.klv.st0102

Enum SecurityMetadataKey

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<SecurityMetadataKey>
      • org.jmisb.api.klv.st0102.SecurityMetadataKey
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<SecurityMetadataKey>, IKlvKey

    public enum SecurityMetadataKey
extends Enum<SecurityMetadataKey>
implements IKlvKey
    ST 0102 key.

    Each metadata element within ST0102 consists of a key represented by a instance of this enumeration, and a value represented by a instance implementing ISecurityMetadataValue.

    The key has two representations - a tag number for the local set, and a universal label for the universal set.

      • SecurityClassification

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey SecurityClassification
        Security Classification.

        Value is a ClassificationLocal in the local set and a ClassificationUniversal in the universal set.

        This item is required for the security local set or universal set to be valid.

      • CcCodingMethod

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey CcCodingMethod
        Coding method for Classifying Country and Releasing Instructions.

        This indicates how the ClassifyingCountry and ReleasingInstructions are to be interpreted. Value is a CountryCodingMethod.

        This item is required for the security local set or universal set to be valid.

      • ClassifyingCountry

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey ClassifyingCountry
        The classifying country.

        This specifies which country classified the data (or possibly which country's security rules / guidance are being used for the classification). Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of CLASSIFYING_COUNTRY and a value corresponding to the country code preceded by //.

        For example, if the CcCodingMethod is ISO3166_THREE_LETTER, then Australia would be represented as new SecurityMetadataString(SecurityMetadataString.CLASSIFYING_COUNTRY, "//AUS").

        This item is required for the security local set or universal set to be valid.

      • SciShiInfo

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey SciShiInfo
        Security Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI) / Special Handling Instructions (SHI) information.

        When special handling instructions or compartmented information are used, Motion Imagery Data shall contain the Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI) / Special Handling Instructions (SHI) metadata element. When used, SCI/SHI digraphs, trigraphs, or compartment names shall be added identifying a single or a combination of special handling instructions.

        A single entry shall be ended with a double forward slash “//”.

        Multiple digraphs, trigraphs, or compartment names shall be separated by a single forward slash “/”.

        Multiple digraphs, trigraphs, or compartment names shall be ended with a double forward slash “//”.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of SCI_SHI_INFO and a value corresponding to the rules above. For example, if the Motion Imagery was in the fictitious "Butter Popcorn" compartment, the value might be: new SecurityMetadataString(SecurityMetadataString.SCI_SHI_INFO, "BUTTER POPCORN//").

      • Caveats

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey Caveats
        Security Caveats.

        The Caveats metadata element represents pertinent caveats (or code words) from each category of the appropriate security entity register. Entries in this field may be abbreviated or spelled out as free text entries.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of CAVEATS and a value of the caveat text or abbreviation. For example, if the Motion Imagery was considered Unclassified, For Official Use Only, the value might be: new SecurityMetadataString(SecurityMetadataString.CAVEATS, "FOUO").

      • ReleasingInstructions

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey ReleasingInstructions
        The countries to which the motion imagery data is releasable to.

        The Releasing Instructions metadata element contains a list of country codes to indicate the countries to which the Motion Imagery Data is releasable.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of RELEASING_INSTRUCTIONS and a value corresponding to the country codes separated by spaces. For example, if the CcCodingMethod is ISO3166_THREE_LETTER, then release to Canada and the United States would be represented as new SecurityMetadataString(SecurityMetadataString.RELEASING_INSTRUCTIONS, "CAN USA").

        This item is required if releasing instructions are required.

      • ClassifiedBy

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey ClassifiedBy
        Classified By.

        The Classified By metadata element identifies the name and type of authority used to classify the Motion Imagery Data. The metadata element is free text and can contain either the original classification authority name and position or personal identifier, or the title of the document or security classification guide used to classify the data.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of CLASSIFIED_BY and a value corresponding to the classified by text. For example, if the classification was performed by "Mark W. Ewing, ODNI Chief Management Officer", it could be shown as new SecurityMetadataString(SecurityMetadataString.CLASSIFIED_BY, "Mark W. Ewing, ODNI Chief Management Officer").

      • DerivedFrom

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey DerivedFrom
        Derived From.

        The Derived From metadata element contains information about the original source of data from which the classification was derived. The metadata element is free text.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of DERIVED_FROM and a value corresponding to the derivative source. For example, if the classification was derived from multiple sources, it could be shown as new SecurityMetadataString(SecurityMetadataString.DERIVED_FROM, "Multiple Sources").

      • ClassificationReason

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey ClassificationReason
        Classification Reason.

        The Classification Reason metadata element contains the reason for classification or a citation from a document. The metadata element is free text.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of CLASSIFICATION_REASON and a value corresponding to the classification reason or citation. For example, if the classification reason is in section 1.4(c), it could be shown as new SecurityMetadataString(SecurityMetadataString.CLASSIFICATION_REASON, "1.4(c)").

      • DeclassificationDate

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey DeclassificationDate
        Declassification Date.

        The Declassification Date metadata element provides a date when the classified material may be automatically declassified.

        Value is a DeclassificationDate. As an example, if the declassification date (from policy) is 31 December 2039, this would be new DeclassificationDate(LocalDate.of(2039, 12, 31)).

      • MarkingSystem

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey MarkingSystem
        Classification and Marking System.

        The Classification and Marking System metadata element identifies the classification or marking system used in the Security Metadata set as determined by the appropriate security entity for the country originating the data. This is free text.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of MARKING_SYSTEM and a value corresponding to the classification and marking system.

      • OcCodingMethod

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey OcCodingMethod
        Object Country Coding Method.

        The Object Country Coding Method metadata element identifies the coding method for the ObjectCountryCodes metadata. This element allows use of GEC two-letter or four-letter alphabetic country code (legacy systems only); ISO-3166 two-letter, three-letter, or three-digit numeric; STANAG 1059 two-letter or three-letter codes; and GENC two-letter, three-letter, three-digit numeric or administrative subdivisions. Early (ST0102-5 and earlier) versions allowed this element to be optional; its absence indicates the default GENC two-letter coding method was used in the Object Country Code element.

        Value is an OcMethod for security metadata local set. For example, new OcMethod(CountryCodingMethod.ISO3166_TWO_LETTER).

        Value is an ObjectCountryCodeString for security metadata universal set.

        This item is required for the security local set or universal set to be valid.

      • ObjectCountryCodes

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey ObjectCountryCodes
        Object Country Codes.

        The Object Country Codes metadata element contains a value identifying the country or countries that are the object of the Motion Imagery Data.

        Multiple Object Country Codes shall be separated by a semi-colon “;” (no spaces).

        The object country code of the geographic region lying under the center of the image frame shall populate the Object Country Code metadata element. The object country codes of other represented geographic regions may be included in addition to the country code of the geographic region under the center of the image frame.

        Value is a ObjectCountryCodeString with a value corresponding to the country code or codes. For example, if the OcCodingMethod is ISO3166_THREE_LETTER, then Australia would be represented as new ObjectCountryCodeString("AUS"). If the imagery also contained part of New Zealand, then it could be represented new ObjectCountryCodeString("AUS;NZL")

      • ClassificationComments

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey ClassificationComments
        Classification Comments.

        The Classification Comments metadata element allows for security related comments and format changes necessary in the future. This field may be used in addition to those required by appropriate security entity and is optional.

        The Classification Comments metadata element shall only be used to convey non-essential security-related information.

        Value is a SecurityMetadataString with a displayName of CLASSIFICATION_COMMENTS and a value providing the free text comments.

      • StreamId

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey StreamId
        Stream Identifier (Deprecated).

        This is a legacy identifier, no longer valid, provided to support ST0102.10 and earlier.

        In MPEG-2 Program Streams and Packetized Elementary Streams (PES) it specifies the type and number of the Elementary Stream. In MPEG-2 Transport Streams the it may be set by the user to any valid value which correctly describes the Elementary Stream type.

        Note that the current MISB position is that the security metadata applies to the information as a whole - there is no marking of individual streams.

        Value is a StreamId. It should not be instantiated, and there is no "construct from value" for StreamId.

      • TransportStreamId

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey TransportStreamId
        Transport Stream Identifier (Deprecated).

        This is a legacy identifier, no longer valid, provided to support ST0102.10 and earlier.

        When multiple Transport Streams are present in a network environment the transport stream identifier uniquely identifies a specific Transport Stream from any other Transport Stream to remove any ambiguity. Its value is defined by the originator.

        Note that the current MISB position is that the security metadata applies to the information as a whole - there is no marking of individual streams.

        Value is a TransportStreamId. It should not be instantiated, and there is no "construct from value" for TransportStreamId.

      • ItemDesignatorId

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey ItemDesignatorId
        Item Designator Identifier (Deprecated).

        This is a legacy identifier, no longer valid, provided to support ST0102.10 and earlier.

        Note that the current MISB position is that the security metadata applies to the information as a whole - there is no marking of individual items.

        Value is an ItemDesignatorId. It should not be instantiated, and there is no "construct from value" for ItemDesignatorId.

      • Version

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey Version
        Version of Security Metadata Standard.

        The Version metadata element indicates the version number of MISB ST 0102 referenced.

        Value is a ST0102Version. As an example, new ST0102Version(SecurityMetadataConstants.ST_VERSION_NUMBER) for the current version supported by jMISB.

      • CcCodingMethodVersionDate

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey CcCodingMethodVersionDate
        Country Coding Method Version Date.

        This metadata item provides the effective date (promulgation date) of the source (FIPS 10-4, ISO 3166, GENC, or STANAG 1059) used for the Classifying Country and Releasing Instructions Country Coding Method. As ISO 3166 is updated by dated circulars, not by version revision, the ISO 8601 YYYY-MM-DD formatted date is used. The valid country codes (and the corresponding meanings) can vary between versions of those coding methods, so this metadata item can be used to identify the exact version of the coding method.

        Value is a CcmDate. For example, if using a GENC baseline of 14 November 2013, this could be new CcmDate(LocalDate.of(2013, 11, 14)).

      • OcCodingMethodVersionDate

        public static final SecurityMetadataKey OcCodingMethodVersionDate
        Object Country Coding Method Version Date.

        This metadata item provides the effective date (promulgation date) of the source (FIPS 10-4, ISO 3166, GENC, or STANAG 1059) used for the Object Country Coding Method. As ISO 3166 is updated by dated circulars, not by version revision, the ISO 8601 YYYY-MM-DD formatted date is used. The valid country codes (and the corresponding meanings) can vary between versions of those coding methods, so this metadata item can be used to identify the exact version of the coding method.

        Value is an OcmDate. For example, if using a GENC baseline of 14 November 2013, this could be new CcmDate(LocalDate.of(2013, 11, 14)).

        public int getIdentifier()

        Get the integer code that corresponds to this key.

        If the parent is a local set, this is the number that the tag uses in a local set. However it can be used in a series as a straight identifier (essentially an index), or in a nested structure as an offset. It is best treated as an opaque identifier.
